{"accepted":[{"assertion":"Formal-Conjectures statement: FC 261 (PR #1902) [in-pr] https://github.com/google-deepmind/formal-conjectures/pull/1902.","id":"vf_787d23975bb3eb71","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"},{"assertion":"Erdős Problem #261: declared status 'open'. Formalized: no. Are there infinitely many $n$ such that there exists some $t\\geq 2$ and distinct integers $a_1,\\ldots,a_t\\geq 1$ such that\\[\\frac{n}{2^n}=\\sum_{1\\leq k\\leq t}\\frac{a_k}{2^{a_k}}?\\]Is this true for all $n$? Is there a rational $x$ such that\\[x = \\sum_{k=1}^\\infty \\frac{a_k}{2^{a_k}}\\]has at least $2^{\\aleph_0}$ solutions? Current best: Erd\\H{o}s does not record what this was, but a later paper by Borwein and Loring \\cite{BoLo90} provides the following proof: for every positive integer $m$ and $n=2^{m+1}-m-2$ we have\\[\\frac{n}{2^n}=\\sum_{n<k\\leq n+m}\\frac{k}{2^k}.\\]Tengely, Ulas, and Zygadlo \\cite{TUZ20} have verified that all $n\\leq 10000$ have the required property. Prize: no. Tags: number theory.","id":"vf_a4ffce7710077e7d","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"}],"accepted_activity":false,"activity":[],"activity_types":[],"attempt_count":0,"banked_attempt_count":0,"commits":[],"dependency_impact":"none","detail_url":"problems/261.json","draft_proposals":[],"edges":[{"evidence":"Problem identity derived from the accepted finding's pinned source anchor.","inferred":true,"relation":"describes","source":"vf_787d23975bb3eb71","source_root":"sha256:1faedc24f040a60a22177b456c74b969a61ce8836082297b1835797a57b4fa56","target":"erdos:261","trust":"signed"},{"evidence":"Materialized typed link between accepted findings.","inferred":true,"relation":"synthesized_from","source":"vf_787d23975bb3eb71","source_root":"sha256:1faedc24f040a60a22177b456c74b969a61ce8836082297b1835797a57b4fa56","target":"vf_a4ffce7710077e7d","trust":"signed"},{"evidence":"Problem identity derived from the accepted finding's pinned source anchor.","inferred":true,"relation":"describes","source":"v